          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Trump threatens Panama</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-24-1.jpg" alt="Trump threatens Panama" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">President-elect Donald Trump <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-1-reignited" target="_blank">reignited</a> controversy over the Panama Canal during Turning Point USA's AmericaFest rally. He called its 1999 transfer to Panama a "foolish" move and suggested it be reclaimed if rising canal tolls persist. He also said that China has too much influence on Panama. While China has <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-2-invested" target="_blank">invested</a> in Panama's infrastructure, the canal is entirely under Panama's jurisdiction. Panama's President José Raúl Mulino rejected Trump's comments, reaffirming the canal's sovereignty and economic significance.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Trump's remarks risk straining generally positive U.S.-Panama relations. The US helped Panama reclaim its sovereignty from Colombia at the beginning of the 20th century. Panama has been a steady ally since the US ouster of dictator Manuel Noriega in 1989. While there is some divide in public opinion of the US, relations remain satisfactory on paper. Also, while the US has some rights to the Panama Canal under the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-3-torrijos-carter-treaty" target="_blank">Torrijos-Carter treaty</a>, they cannot reclaim it.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


