          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Grasping for gratitude</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">French President Emmanuel Macron faced <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-7-backlash" target="_blank">backlash</a> during his visit to Mayotte, a French overseas department hit by Cyclone Chido, which left at least 31 dead and caused widespread destruction. Macron was heckled by the residents with chants of “resign” and demanded more assistance, citing a lack of food, water, and electricity. He made things worse when he defended France’s efforts, arguing that conditions would be far worse without its support. He stated, “If this weren’t France, you’d be 10,000 times more in the sh*t.” He was referring to the aid from the mainland, and France’s disaster response angered residents.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Opposition politicians accused Macron of insensitivity, with some labeling his remarks humiliating to victims. Cyclone Chido’s devastation is described as one of the worst disasters in nearly a century. France’s response to the crisis has been scrutinized. France has been dealing with issues from other overseas departments, such as <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-8-new-caledonia" target="_blank">New Caledonia</a></p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

