          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">How was the Panama Canal created?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-24-3.jpg" alt="foundations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-12-panama-canal" target="_blank">Panama Canal</a>, which connects the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, revolutionized global trade by eliminating the need for ships to navigate around South America. France attempted it earlier, but it was a major failure. The U.S. took over the project in 1904 after supporting Panama’s independence from Colombia and securing canal rights. Under President Theodore Roosevelt, the U.S. implemented innovative measures, including constructing locks to lift ships over mountains and creating Gatun Lake with the Gatun Dam. The canal was completed in 1914.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">For most of the  20th century, the U.S. managed and operated the canal, maintaining military bases in the Canal Zone and overseeing its governance and defense. The agreements in the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-dec-2024-13-torrijos-carter-treaties" target="_blank">Torrijos-Carter Treaties</a> resulted in the gradual transfer of canal control to Panama by December 31, 1999. The treaties ended U.S. sovereignty over the Canal Zone but granted the U.S. the right to defend the canal's neutrality.​</p>
        </mj-text>
